    <text>
        <body>
             <div type="edition" subtype="ogham" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="pgl-Ogam" resp="#POC">              
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:up-down"/><persName><name nymRef="#?">ᚁᚏᚑ<supplied reason="lost">ᚔᚅᚔᚑᚅ</supplied>ᚐᚄ</name></persName>
                </ab> 
            </div>                    
            <div type="edition" subtype="transliteration" xml:lang="pgl-Ogam" xml:space="preserve" resp="#POC">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:up-down"/><persName><name nymRef="#?">BRO<supplied reason="lost">INION</supplied>AS</name></persName>
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                <app n="1">
            <note>According to Macalister (1945, 275-6), -INION- <q>would just about fill the missing portion</q> of the inscription. Three notches of the first possible I remain. </note>                    
                </app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation">
                <p>'of Bróen?'</p> 
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>The name BROINIONAS is recorded in three other ogham inscriptions ((I-COR-071) Monataggart, Co. Cork; (I-KER-018) Ballinrannig, Co. Kerry and CIIC 295 Knockboy, Co Waterford). However, the reading is only relatively certain in (I-KER-018) Ballinrannig, Co. Kerry, which has the expected ending -IONAS and in (I-COR-071) Monataggart, Co. Cork, which has BROINIENAS.</p>
            </div>
